# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-62304-medical
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-62304-medical/iec-62304] The IEC 62304 standard calls out certain cautions on using software, particularly SOUP (software of unknown pedigree or provenance).
[src:iec-62304-medical/iec-62304] The standard spells out a risk-based decision model on when the use of SOUP is acceptable, and defines testing requirements for SOUP to support a rationale on why such software should be used.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] The current ISO 13485 edition was published on 1 March 2016.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] While it remains a stand-alone document, ISO 13485 is generally harmonized with ISO 9001.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] A principal difference, however, is that ISO 9001 requires the organization to demonstrate continual improvement, whereas ISO 13485 requires only that the certified organization demonstrate the quality system is effectively implemented and maintained.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] Additionally, the ISO 9001 requirements regarding customer satisfaction are absent from the medical device standard.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] ISO 13485 places specific emphasis on resource and environment management, tailored to the medical device and software sectors.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] For example, the standard requires organizations to ensure that their personnel are not only qualified but also adequately trained to understand and implement regulatory requirements.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] Moreover, the infrastructure and work environment must support compliance and safety.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] In software engineering for medical devices, this extends to maintaining cybersecurity measures and ensuring a development environment free from potential risks to data integrity or software reliability.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] Compliance with ISO 13485 is often seen as the first step in achieving compliance with European regulatory requirements.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] The conformity of Medical Devices and In-vitro Diagnostic Medical Device according to European Union Directives 93/42/EEC, 90/385/EEC and 98/79/EEC must be assessed before sale is permitted.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] One of the major requirements to prove conformity is the implementation of the Quality Management System according ISO 9001 and/or ISO 13485 and ISO 14971.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] Although the European Union Directives do not mandate certification to ISO 9001 and/or ISO 13485 the preferred method to prove compliance to such standards is to seek its official certification which is issued by certifying organizations known as "Registrars".
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] Several registrars also act as Notified Body.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] For those medical devices requiring the pre-market involvement of a Notified Body, the result of a positive assessment from the Notified Body is the certificate of conformity allowing the CE mark and the permission to sell the medical device in the European Union.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] A very careful assessment of the company Quality Management System by the Notified Body, together with the review of the required Technical Documentation, is a major element which the Notified Body takes into account to issue the certificate of conformity to the company product(s).
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] This standard adopted by CEN as EN ISO 13485:2003/AC:2007 is harmonized with respect to the European medical device regulations (MDR & IVDR).
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] ISO 13485 is now considered to be inline standard and requirement for medical devices even with "Global Harmonization Task Force Guidelines" (GHTF).
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] The GHTF guidelines are slowly becoming universal standards for design, manufacture, export and sales of various medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] The GHTF has been replaced in the last few years by the International Medical Device Regulators Forum (IMDRF) and is structured differently from the GHTF as only the regulators, that are primary members of the group, get to make many of the decisions.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] This standard adopted by CEN as EN ISO 13485:2016 is harmonized with respect to the European Medical Device Regulation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] Mexico published on October 11, 2012, a national standard as a Norma Oficial Mexicana (NOM) to control manufacture of medical devices inside the country.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] NOM-241-SSA1-2012, Buenas Practicas de Fabricación para Establecimientos dedicados a la Fabricación de Dispositivos Médicos.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] The scope of application is mandatory in the national territory, for all establishments dedicated to the process of medical devices marketed in the country.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] The Cofepris is the body assigned to its control, verification and to grant the records of compliance to the companies that implement this Standard of Good Manufacturing Practices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] This standard is partially in line with ISO 13485: 2003 and ISO 9001: 2008.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] This standard will be published in August 2018, and 180 days after publication it will become mandatory for the industry.
[src:iec-62304-medical/iso-13485] Medical devices include products of the following categories: medical equipment, prostheses, orthotics, functional aids, diagnostic agents, supplies for dental use, surgical, healing and hygiene products.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] A **medical device** is any device intended to be used for medical purposes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Significant potential for hazards are inherent when using a device for medical purposes and thus medical devices must be proved safe and effective with reasonable assurance before regulating governments allow marketing of the device in their country.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] As a general rule, as the associated risk of the device increases the amount of testing required to establish safety and efficacy also increases.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Further, as associated risk increases the potential benefit to the patient must also increase.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Discovery of what would be considered a medical device by modern standards dates as far back as c.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] 7000 BC in Baluchistan where Neolithic dentists used flint-tipped drills and bowstrings.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Study of archeology and Roman medical literature also indicate that many types of medical devices were in widespread use during the time of ancient Rome.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In the United States, it was not until the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act (FD&C Act) in 1938 that medical devices were regulated at all.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] It was not until later in 1976 that the Medical Device Amendments to the FD&C Act established medical device regulation and oversight as we know it today in the United States.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical device regulation in Europe as we know it today came into effect in 1993 by what is collectively known as the Medical Device Directive (MDD).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] On May 26, 2017, the Medical Device Regulation (MDR) replaced the MDD.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical devices vary in both their intended use and indications for use.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Examples range from simple, low-risk devices such as tongue depressors, medical thermometers, disposable gloves, and bedpans to complex, high-risk devices that are implanted and sustain life.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Examples of high-risk devices include artificial hearts, pacemakers, joint replacements, and CT scans.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The design of medical devices constitutes a major segment of the field of biomedical engineering.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The global medical device market was estimated to be between $220 and US$250 billion in 2013.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The United States controls ≈40% of the global market followed by Europe (25%), Japan (15%), and the rest of the world (20%).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Although collectively Europe has a larger share, Japan has the second largest country market share.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The largest market shares in Europe (in order of market share size) belong to Germany, Italy, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The rest of the world comprises regions like (in no particular order) Australia, Canada, China, India, and Iran.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] A global definition for medical device is difficult to establish because there are numerous regulatory bodies worldwide overseeing the marketing of medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Although these bodies often collaborate and discuss the definition in general, there are subtle differences in wording that prevent a global harmonization of the definition of a medical device, thus the appropriate definition of a medical device depends on the region.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Often a portion of the definition of a medical device is intended to differentiate between medical devices and drugs, as the regulatory requirements of the two are different.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Definitions also often recognize In vitro diagnostics as a subclass of medical devices and establish accessories as medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] which does not achieve its primary intended purposes through chemical action within or on the body of man or other animals and which is not dependent upon being metabolized for the achievement of its primary intended purposes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] According to Article 1 of Council Directive 93/42/EEC, on 26 May 2021, the definition of a medical device in the European Union is now governed by the Medical Devices Regulation (MDR) (EU) 2017/745.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Based on the *New Approach*, rules that relate to safety and performance of medical devices were harmonised in the EU in the 1990s.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The *New Approach*, defined in a European Council Resolution of May 1985, represents an innovative way of technical harmonisation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] It aims to remove technical barriers to trade and dispel the consequent uncertainty for economic operators, to facilitate free movement of goods inside the EU.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] They aim at ensuring a high level of protection of human health and safety and the good functioning of the Single Market.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] These three main directives have been supplemented over time by several modifying and implementing directives, including the last technical revision brought about by Directive 2007/47 EC.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The government of each Member State must appoint a *competent authority* responsible for medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The competent authority (CA) is a body with authority to act on behalf of the member state to ensure that member state government transposes requirements of medical device directives into national law and applies them.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The CA reports to the minister of health in the member state.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The CA in one Member State has no jurisdiction in any other member state, but exchanges information and tries to reach common positions.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In the UK, for example, the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) acted as a CA.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In Italy it is the Ministero Salute (Ministry of Health) Medical devices must not be mistaken with medicinal products.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In the EU, all medical devices must be identified with the CE mark.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The conformity of a medium or high risk medical device with relevant regulations is also assessed by an external entity, the Notified Body, before it can be placed on the market.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In September 2012, the European Commission proposed new legislation aimed at enhancing safety, traceability, and transparency.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The two regulations are supplemented by several guidances developed by the Medical Devices Coordination Group (MDCG).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The term covers a wide range of health or medical instruments used in the treatment, mitigation, diagnosis or prevention of a disease or abnormal physical condition.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Health Canada reviews medical devices to assess their safety, effectiveness, and quality before authorizing their sale in Canada.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] According to the Act, medical device does not include any device that is intended for use in relation to animals.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] India has introduced National Medical Device Policy 2023.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] However, certain medical devices are notified as DRUGS under the Drugs & Cosmetics Act.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Section 3 (b) (iv) relating to definition of "drugs" holds that "Devices intended for internal or external use in the diagnosis, treatment, mitigation or prevention of disease or disorder in human beings or animals" are also drugs.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] As of April 2022, 14 classes of devices are classified as drugs.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The regulatory authorities recognize different classes of medical devices based on their potential for harm if misused, design complexity, and their use characteristics.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Each country or region defines these categories in different ways.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The authorities also recognize that some devices are provided in combination with drugs, and regulation of these combination products takes this factor into consideration.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Classifying medical devices based on their risk is essential for maintaining patient and staff safety while simultaneously facilitating the marketing of medical products.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] By establishing different risk classifications, lower risk devices, for example, a stethoscope or tongue depressor, are not required to undergo the same level of testing that higher risk devices such as artificial pacemakers undergo.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Establishing a hierarchy of risk classification allows regulatory bodies to provide flexibility when reviewing medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Under the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act, the U.S.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Food and Drug Administration recognizes three classes of medical devices, based on the level of control necessary to assure safety and effectiveness.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The classification procedures are described in the Code of Federal Regulations, Title 21, part 860 (usually known as 21 CFR 860).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Class I devices are subject to the least regulatory control and are not intended to help support or sustain life or be substantially important in preventing impairment to human health, and may not present an unreasonable risk of illness or injury.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Examples of Class I devices include elastic bandages, examination gloves, and hand-held surgical instruments.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Class II devices are subject to special labeling requirements, mandatory performance standards and postmarket surveillance.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Examples of Class II devices include acupuncture needles, powered wheelchairs, infusion pumps, air purifiers, surgical drapes, stereotaxic navigation systems, and surgical robots.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Class III devices are usually those that support or sustain human life, are of substantial importance in preventing impairment of human health, or present a potential, unreasonable risk of illness or injury and require premarket approval.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Examples of Class III devices include implantable pacemakers, pulse generators, HIV diagnostic tests, automated external defibrillators, and endosseous implants.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The classification of medical devices in the European Union is outlined in Article IX of the Council Directive 93/42/EEC and Annex VIII of the EU medical device regulation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The authorization of medical devices is guaranteed by a Declaration of Conformity.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] This declaration is issued by the manufacturer itself, but for products in Class Is, Im, Ir, IIa, IIb or III, it must be verified by a Certificate of Conformity issued by a Notified Body.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] A Notified Body is a public or private organisation that has been accredited to validate the compliance of the device to the European Directive.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical devices that pertain to class I (on condition they do not require sterilization or do not measure a function) can be marketed purely by self-certification.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The European classification depends on rules that involve the medical device's duration of body contact, invasive character, use of an energy source, effect on the central circulation or nervous system, diagnostic impact, or incorporation of a medicinal product.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Certified medical devices should have the CE mark on the packaging, insert leaflets, etc..
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] These packagings should also show harmonised pictograms and EN standardised logos to indicate essential features such as instructions for use, expiry date, manufacturer, sterile, do not reuse, etc.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In November 2018, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland decided that the "Sympto" app, used to analyze a woman's menstrual cycle, was a medical device because it calculates a fertility window for each woman using personal data.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Classes I and II distinguish between extremely low and low risk devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Classes III and IV, moderate and high risk respectively, are highly and specially controlled medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In vitro diagnostics have three risk classifications.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] For the remaining regions in the world, the risk classifications are generally similar to the United States, European Union, and Japan or are a variant combining two or more of the three countries' risk classifications.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The *ASEAN Medical Device Directive* (AMDD) has been adopted by several southeast Asian countries.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The nations are at varying stages of adopting and implementing the Directive.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The AMDD classification is risk-based and defines four levels: A - Low Risk, B - Low to Moderate Risk, C - Moderate – High Risk, and D - High Risk.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The classification of medical devices in Australia is outlined in section 41BD of the Therapeutic Goods Act 1989 and Regulation 3.2 of the Therapeutic Goods Regulations 2002, under control of the Therapeutic Goods Administration.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Similarly to the EU classification, they rank in several categories, by order of increasing risk and associated required level of control.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The Medical Devices Bureau of Health Canada recognizes four classes of medical devices based on the level of control necessary to assure the safety and effectiveness of the device.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Class I devices present the lowest potential risk and do not require a licence.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Class II devices require the manufacturer's declaration of device safety and effectiveness, whereas Class III and IV devices present a greater potential risk and are subject to in-depth scrutiny.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] A guidance document for device classification is published by Health Canada.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Examples include surgical instruments (Class I), contact lenses and ultrasound scanners (Class II), orthopedic implants and hemodialysis machines (Class III), and cardiac pacemakers (Class IV).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical devices in India are regulated by Central Drugs Standard Control Organisation (CDSCO).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical devices under the Medical Devices Rules, 2017 are classified as per Global Harmonization Task Force (GHTF) based on associated risks.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The CDSCO classifications of medical devices govern alongside the regulatory approval and registration by the CDSCO is under the DCGI.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Every single medical device in India pursues a regulatory framework that depends on the drug guidelines under the Drug and Cosmetics Act (1940) and the Drugs and Cosmetics runs under 1945.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] CDSCO classification for medical devices has a set of risk classifications for numerous products planned for notification and guidelines as medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Iran produces about 2,000 types of medical devices and medical supplies, such as appliances, dental supplies, disposable sterile medical items, laboratory machines, various biomaterials and dental implants.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] 400 Medical products are produced at the C and D risk class with all of them licensed by the Iranian Health Ministry in terms of safety and performance based on EU-standards.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Some Iranian medical devices are produced according to the European Union standards.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Some producers in Iran export medical devices and supplies which adhere to European Union standards to applicant countries, including 40 Asian and European countries.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Some Iranian producers export their products to foreign countries.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Following Brexit, the UK medical device regulation was closely aligned with the EU medical device regulation, including classification.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Validation and verification of medical devices ensure that they fulfil their intended purpose.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Validation or verification is generally needed when a health facility acquires a new device to perform medical tests.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The main difference between the two is that validation is focused on ensuring that the device meets the needs and requirements of its intended users and the intended use environment, whereas verification is focused on ensuring that the device meets its specified design requirements.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The ISO standards for medical devices are covered by ICS 11.100.20 and 11.040.01.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The quality and risk management regarding the topic for regulatory purposes is convened by ISO 13485 and ISO 14971.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] ISO 13485:2016 is applicable to all providers and manufacturers of medical devices, components, contract services and distributors of medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The standard is the basis for regulatory compliance in local markets, and most export markets.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Additionally, ISO 9001:2008 sets precedence because it signifies that a company engages in the creation of new products.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] It requires that the development of manufactured products have an approval process and a set of rigorous quality standards and development records before the product is distributed.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Further standards are IEC 60601-1 which is for electrical devices (mains-powered as well as battery powered), EN 45502-1 which is for Active implantable medical devices, and IEC 62304 for medical software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The US FDA also published a series of guidances for industry regarding this topic against 21 CFR 820 Subchapter H—Medical Devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Subpart B includes quality system requirements, an important component of which are design controls (21 CFR 820.30).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] To meet the demands of these industry regulation standards, a growing number of medical device distributors are putting the complaint management process at the forefront of their quality management practices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] This approach further mitigates risks and increases visibility of quality issues.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Starting in the late 1980s, the FDA increased its involvement in reviewing the development of medical device software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The precipitant for change was a radiation therapy device (Therac-25) that overdosed patients because of software coding errors.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] FDA is now focused on regulatory oversight on medical device software development process and system-level testing.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Diana Zuckerman and Paul Brown of the National Center for Health Research, and Dr.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Steven Nissen of the Cleveland Clinic, published in the *Archives of Internal Medicine*, showed that most medical devices recalled in the last five years for "serious health problems or death" had been previously approved by the FDA using the less stringent, and cheaper, 510(k) process.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In a few cases, the devices had been deemed so low-risk that they did not they did not undergo any FDA regulatory review.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Of the 113 devices recalled, 35 were for cardiovascular issues.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] This study was the topic of Congressional hearings re-evaluating FDA procedures and oversight.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Aditi Das of the National Center for Health Research, published in JAMA Internal Medicine, examined the scientific evidence that is publicly available about medical implants that were cleared by the FDA 510(k) process from 2008 to 2012.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] They found that scientific evidence supporting "substantial equivalence" to other devices already on the market was required by law to be publicly available, but the information was available for only 16% of the randomly selected implants, and only 10% provided clinical data.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Of the more than 1,100 predicate implants that the new implants were substantially equivalent to, only 3% had any publicly available scientific evidence, and only 1% had clinical evidence of safety or effectiveness.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The researchers concluded that publicly available scientific evidence on implants was needed to protect the public health.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In 2014–2015, a new international agreement, the Medical Device Single Audit Program (MDSAP), was put in place with five participant countries: Australia, Brazil, Canada, Japan, and the United States.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The aim of this program was to "develop a process that allows a single audit, or inspection to ensure the medical device regulatory requirements for all five countries are satisfied".
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Diana Zuckerman published in the peer-reviewed policy journal Milbank Quarterly found that electronic health records and other device software were recalled due to life-threatening flaws.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The article pointed out the lack of safeguards against hacking and other cybersecurity threats, stating "current regulations are necessary but not sufficient for ensuring patient safety by identifying and eliminating dangerous defects in software currently on the market".
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] They added that legislative changes resulting from the law entitled the 21st Century Cures Act "will further deregulate health IT, reducing safeguards that facilitate the reporting and timely recall of flawed medical software that could harm patients".
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The law encourages patient diversity in clinical trials submitted to the FDA for review, but does not require it.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The study determined that most high-risk medical devices are not tested and analyzed to ensure that they are safe and effective for all major demographic groups, particularly racial and ethnic minorities and people over 65.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Therefore, they do not provide information about safety or effectiveness that would help patients and physicians make well informed decisions.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical device packaging is highly regulated.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Often medical devices and products are sterilized in the package.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Sterility must be maintained throughout distribution to allow immediate use by physicians.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] A series of special packaging tests measure the ability of the package to maintain sterility.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Package testing is part of a quality management system including verification and validation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] It is important to document and ensure that packages meet regulations and end-use requirements.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Manufacturing processes must be controlled and validated to ensure consistent performance.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] EN ISO 15223-1 defines symbols that can be used to convey important information on packaging and labeling.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical device cleanliness has come under greater scrutiny since 2000, when Sulzer Orthopedics recalled several thousand metal hip implants that contained a manufacturing residue.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Based on this event, ASTM established a new task group (F04.15.17) for established test methods, guidance documents, and other standards to address cleanliness of medical devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] This task group has issued two standards for permanent implants to date: 1.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] ASTM F2459: Standard test method for extracting residue from metallic medical components and quantifying via gravimetric analysis 2.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] ASTM F2847: Standard Practice for Reporting and Assessment of Residues on Single Use Implants 3.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The ASTM F04.15.17 task group is working on several new standards that involve designing implants for cleaning, selection and testing of brushes for cleaning reusable devices, and cleaning assessment of medical devices made by additive manufacturing.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Additionally, the FDA is establishing new guidelines for reprocessing reusable medical devices, such as orthoscopic shavers, endoscopes, and suction tubes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] New research was published in ACS Applied Interfaces and Material to keep Medical Tools pathogen free.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical device manufacturing requires a level of process control according to the classification of the device.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] When in the initial R&D phase, manufacturers are now beginning to design for manufacturability.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] This means products can be more precision-engineered to for production to result in shorter lead times, tighter tolerances and more advanced specifications and prototypes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The arrival of CAD and other modelling platforms accelerated this process, acting both as a tool for strategic design generation and marketing.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Failure to meet cost targets will lead to substantial losses for an organisation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In addition, with global competition, the R&D of new devices is not just a necessity, it is an imperative for medical device manufacturers.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The realisation of a new design can be very costly, especially with the shorter product life cycle.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] As technology advances, there is typically a level of quality, safety and reliability that increases exponentially with time.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] For example, initial models of the artificial cardiac pacemaker were external support devices that transmits pulses of electricity to the heart muscles via electrode leads on the chest.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The electrodes contact the heart directly through the chest, allowing stimulation pulses to pass through the body.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Recipients of this typically developed an infection at the entrance of the electrodes, which led to the subsequent trial of the first internal pacemaker, with electrodes attached to the myocardium by thoracotomy.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Future developments led to the isotope-power source that would last for the lifespan of the patient.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] With the rise of smartphone usage in the medical space, in 2013, the FDA issued to regulate mobile medical applications and protect users from their unintended use, soon followed by European and other regulatory agencies.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] This guidance distinguishes the apps subjected to regulation based on the marketing claims of the apps.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Incorporation of the guidelines during the development phase of such apps can be considered as developing a medical device; the regulations have to adapt and propositions for expedite approval may be required due to the nature of 'versions' of mobile application development.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] On September 25, 2013, the FDA released a draft guidance document for regulation of mobile medical applications, to clarify what kind of mobile apps related to health would not be regulated, and which would be.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical devices such as pacemakers, insulin pumps, operating room monitors, defibrillators, and surgical instruments, including deep-brain stimulators, can incorporate the ability to transmit vital health information from a patient's body to medical professionals.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Some of these devices can be remotely controlled.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] This has engendered concern about privacy and security issues, human error, and technical glitches with this technology.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] While only a few studies have looked at the susceptibility of medical devices to hacking, there is a risk.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In 2008, computer scientists proved that pacemakers and defibrillators can be hacked wirelessly via radio hardware, an antenna, and a personal computer.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] These researchers showed they could shut down a combination heart defibrillator and pacemaker and reprogram it to deliver potentially lethal shocks or run out its battery.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Jay Radcliff, a security researcher interested in the security of medical devices, raised fears about the safety of these devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] He shared his concerns at the Black Hat security conference.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Radcliff fears that the devices are vulnerable and has found that a lethal attack is possible against those with insulin pumps and glucose monitors.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Some medical device makers downplay the threat from such attacks and argue that the demonstrated attacks have been performed by skilled security researchers and are unlikely to occur in the real world.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] At the same time, other makers have asked software security experts to investigate the safety of their devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In June 2011, security experts showed that by using readily available hardware and a user manual, a scientist could tap into the information on the system of a wireless insulin pump in combination with a glucose monitor.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] With the PIN of the device, the scientist could wirelessly control the dosage of the insulin.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Anand Raghunathan, a researcher in this study, explains that medical devices are getting smaller and lighter so that they can be easily worn.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The downside is that additional security features would put an extra strain on the battery and size and drive up prices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] William Maisel offered some thoughts on the motivation to engage in this activity.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Motivation to do this hacking might include acquisition of private information for financial gain or competitive advantage; damage to a device manufacturer's reputation; sabotage; intent to inflict financial or personal injury or just satisfaction for the attacker.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Another solution is to use a technology called "body-coupled communication" that uses the human skin as a wave guide for wireless communication.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] On 28 December 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration released its recommendations that are not legally enforceable for how medical device manufacturers should maintain the security of Internet-connected devices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Similar to hazards, cybersecurity threats and vulnerabilities cannot be eliminated but must be managed and reduced to a reasonable level.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] When designing medical devices, the tier of cybersecurity risk should be determined early in the process in order to establish a cybersecurity vulnerability and management approach (including a set of cybersecurity design controls).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The medical device design approach employed should be consistent with the NIST Cybersecurity Framework for managing cybersecurity-related risks.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In August 2013, the FDA released over 20 regulations aiming to improve the security of data in medical devices, in response to the growing risks of limited cybersecurity.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The number of approved medical devices using artificial intelligence or machine learning (AI/ML) is increasing.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] As of 2020, there were several hundred AI/ML medical devices approved by the US FDA or CE-marked devices in Europe.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Most AI/ML devices focus upon radiology.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] As of 2020, there was no specific regulatory pathway for AI/ML-based medical devices in the US or Europe.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] However, in January 2021, the FDA published a proposed regulatory framework for AI/ML-based software, and the EU medical device regulation which replaces the EU Medical Device Directive in May 2021, defines regulatory requirements for medical devices, including AI/ML software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In January 2025, the FDA published a draft guidance document for AI-enabled medical devices, covering both lifecycle considerations and marketing submissions.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The identification of medical devices has been recently improved by the introduction of Unique Device Identification (UDI) and standardised naming using the Global Medical Device Nomenclature (GMDN) which have been endorsed by the International Medical Device Regulatory Forum (IMDRF).
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] A biomedical equipment technician (BMET) is a vital component of the healthcare delivery system.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Employed primarily by hospitals, BMETs are the people responsible for maintaining a facility's medical equipment.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] BMET mainly act as an interface between doctor and equipment.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] There are challenges surrounding the availability of medical equipment from a global health perspective, with low-resource countries unable to obtain or afford essential and life-saving equipment.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] In these settings, well-intentioned equipment donation from high- to low-resource settings is a frequently used strategy to address this through individuals, organisations, manufacturers and charities.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] However, issues with maintenance, availability of biomedical equipment technicians (BMET), supply chains, user education and the appropriateness of donations means these frequently fail to deliver the intended benefits.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The WHO estimates that 95% of medical equipment in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs) is imported and 80% of it is funded by international donors or foreign governments.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] While up to 70% of medical equipment in sub-Saharan Africa is donated, only 10%–30% of donated equipment becomes operational.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] A review of current practice and guidelines for the donation of medical equipment for surgical and anaesthesia care in LMICs has demonstrated a high level of complexity within the donation process and numerous shortcomings.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Greater collaboration and planning between donors and recipients is required together with evaluation of donation programs and concerted advocacy to educate donors and recipients on existing equipment donation guidelines and policies.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The circulation of medical equipment is not limited to donations.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] The rise of reuse and recycle-based solutions, where gently used medical equipment is donated and redistributed to communities in need, is another form of equipment distribution.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] An interest in reusing and recycling emerged in the 1980s when the potential health hazards of medical waste on the East Coast beaches became highlighted by the media.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Connecting the large demand for medical equipment and single-use medical devices, with a need for waste reduction, as well as the problem of unequal access for low-income communities led to the Congress enacting the Medical Waste Tracking Act of 1988.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical equipment can be donated either by governments or non-governmental organizations, domestic or international.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Donated equipment ranges from bedside assistance to radiological equipment.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Medical equipment donation has come under scrutiny with regard to donated-device failure and loss of warranty in the case of previous-ownership.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Most medical devices and production company warranties do not extend to reused or donated devices, or to devices donated by initial owners/patients.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Such reuse raises matters of patient autonomy, medical ethics, and legality.
[src:iec-62304-medical/medical-device] Such concerns conflict with the importance of equal access to healthcare resources, and the goal of serving the greatest good for the greatest number.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] A **safety-related system** (or sometimes **safety-involved system**) comprises everything (hardware, software, and human aspects) needed to perform one or more safety functions, in which failure would cause a significant increase in the safety risk for the people or environment involved.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Safety-related systems are those that do not have full responsibility for controlling hazards such as loss of life, severe injury or severe environmental damage.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] The malfunction of a safety-involved system would only be that hazardous in conjunction with the failure of other systems or human error.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Some safety organizations provide guidance on safety-related systems, for example the Health and Safety Executive in the United Kingdom.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Risks of this sort are usually managed with the methods and tools of safety engineering.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] A safety-critical system is designed to lose less than one life per billion (109) hours of operation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Typical design methods include probabilistic risk assessment, a method that combines failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA) with fault tree analysis.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Safety-critical systems are increasingly computer-based.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Safety-critical systems are a concept often used together with the Swiss cheese model to represent (usually in a bow-tie diagram) how a threat can escalate to a major accident through the failure of multiple critical barriers.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] This use has become common especially in the domain of process safety, in particular when applied to oil and gas drilling and production both for illustrative purposes and to support other processes, such as asset integrity management and incident investigation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Software engineering for safety-critical systems is particularly difficult.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] There are three aspects which can be applied to aid the engineering software for life-critical systems.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] First is process engineering and management.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Secondly, selecting the appropriate tools and environment for the system.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] This allows the system developer to effectively test the system by emulation and observe its effectiveness.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Thirdly, address any legal and regulatory requirements, such as Federal Aviation Administration requirements for aviation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] By setting a standard for which a system is required to be developed under, it forces the designers to stick to the requirements.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] The avionics industry has succeeded in producing standard methods for producing life-critical avionics software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Similar standards exist for industry, in general, (IEC 61508) and automotive (ISO 26262), medical (IEC 62304) and nuclear (IEC 61513) industries specifically.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] The standard approach is to carefully code, inspect, document, test, verify and analyze the system.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Another approach is to certify a production system, a compiler, and then generate the system's code from specifications.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] Another approach uses formal methods to generate proofs that the code meets requirements.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] All of these approaches improve the software quality in safety-critical systems by testing or eliminating manual steps in the development process, because people make mistakes, and these mistakes are the most common cause of potential life-threatening errors.
[src:iec-62304-medical/safety-critical-system] The technology requirements can go beyond avoidance of failure, and can even facilitate medical *intensive care* (which deals with healing patients), and also *life support* (which is for stabilizing patients).
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] A **software development process** prescribes a process for developing software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] It typically divides an overall effort into smaller steps or sub-processes that are intended to ensure high-quality results.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The process may describe specific deliverables – artifacts to be created and completed.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Although not strictly limited to it, software development process often refers to the high-level process that governs the development of a software system from its beginning to its end of life – known as a methodology, model or framework.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The system development life cycle (SDLC) describes the typical phases that a development effort goes through from the beginning to the end of life for a system – including a software system.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] A methodology prescribes how engineers go about their work in order to move the system through its life cycle.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] A methodology is a classification of processes or a blueprint for a process that is devised for the SDLC.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] For example, many processes can be classified as a spiral model.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Software process and software quality are closely interrelated; some unexpected facets and effects have been observed in practice.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The SDLC drives the definition of a methodology in that a methodology must address the phases of the SDLC.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Generally, a methodology is designed to result in a high-quality system that meets or exceeds expectations (requirements) and is delivered on time and within budget even though computer systems can be complex and integrate disparate components.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Various methodologies have been devised, including waterfall, spiral, agile, rapid prototyping, incremental, and synchronize and stabilize.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] A major difference between methodologies is the degree to which the phases are sequential vs. iterative.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Agile methodologies, such as XP and scrum, focus on lightweight processes that allow for rapid changes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Iterative methodologies, such as Rational Unified Process and dynamic systems development method, focus on stabilizing project scope and iteratively expanding or improving products.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Sequential or big-design-up-front (BDUF) models, such as waterfall, focus on complete and correct planning to guide larger projects and limit risks to successful and predictable results.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Anamorphic development is guided by project scope and adaptive iterations.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] In scrum, for example, one could say a single user story goes through all the phases of the SDLC within a two-week sprint.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] By contrast the waterfall methodology, where every business requirement is translated into feature/functional descriptions which are then all implemented typically over a period of months or longer.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] A project can include both a project life cycle (PLC) and an SDLC, which describe different activities.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] According to Taylor (2004), "the project life cycle encompasses all the activities of the project, while the systems development life cycle focuses on realizing the product requirements".
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The term *SDLC* is often used as an abbreviated version of *SDLC methodology*.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Further, some use *SDLC* and *traditional SDLC* to mean the waterfall methodology.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] According to Elliott (2004), SDLC "originated in the 1960s, to develop large scale functional business systems in an age of large scale business conglomerates.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Information systems activities revolved around heavy data processing and number crunching routines".
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The structured systems analysis and design method (SSADM) was produced for the UK government Office of Government Commerce in the 1980s.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Ever since, according to Elliott (2004), "the traditional life cycle approaches to systems development have been increasingly replaced with alternative approaches and frameworks, which attempted to overcome some of the inherent deficiencies of the traditional SDLC".
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Since DSDM in 1994, all of the methodologies on the above list except RUP have been agile methodologies - yet many organizations, especially governments, still use pre-agile processes (often waterfall or similar).
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The following are notable methodologies somewhat ordered by popularity.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Agile software development refers to a group of frameworks based on iterative development, where requirements and solutions evolve via collaboration between self-organizing cross-functional teams.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The term was coined in the year 2001 when the Agile Manifesto was formulated.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The waterfall model is a sequential development approach, in which development flows one way (like a waterfall) through the SDLC phases.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] In 1988, Barry Boehm published a software system development spiral model, which combines key aspects of the waterfall model and rapid prototyping, in an effort to combine advantages of top-down and bottom-up concepts.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] It emphases a key area many felt had been neglected by other methodologies: deliberate iterative risk analysis, particularly suited to large-scale complex systems.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Various methods combine linear and iterative methodologies, with the primary objective of reducing inherent project risk by breaking a project into smaller segments and providing more ease-of-change during the development process.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Software prototyping is about creating prototypes, i.e. incomplete versions of the software program being developed.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Rapid application development (RAD) is a methodology which favors iterative development and the rapid construction of prototypes instead of large amounts of up-front planning.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The "planning" of software developed using RAD is interleaved with writing the software itself.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The lack of extensive pre-planning generally allows software to be written much faster and makes it easier to change requirements.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Shape Up is a software development approach introduced by Basecamp in 2018.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] It is a set of principles and techniques that Basecamp developed internally to overcome the problem of projects dragging on with no clear end.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Its primary target audience is remote teams.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Shape Up has no estimation and velocity tracking, backlogs, or sprints, unlike waterfall, agile, or scrum.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Instead, those concepts are replaced with appetite, betting, and cycles.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] As of 2022, besides Basecamp, notable organizations that have adopted Shape Up include UserVoice and Block.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Chaos model has one main rule: always resolve the most important issue first.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Incremental funding methodology - an iterative approach.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Lightweight methodology - a general term for methods that only have a few rules and practices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Structured systems analysis and design method - a specific version of waterfall.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] As part of the larger slow movement, emphasizes careful and gradual work without (or minimal) time pressures.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Slow programming aims to avoid bugs and overly quick release schedules.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] V-Model (software development) - an extension of the waterfall model.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Unified Process (UP) is an iterative software development methodology framework, based on Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] UP organizes the development of software into four phases, each consisting of one or more executable iterations of the software at that stage of development: inception, elaboration, construction, and guidelines.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The waterfall model describes the SDLC phases such that each builds on the result of the previous one.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Not every project requires that the phases be sequential.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] For relatively simple projects, phases may be combined or overlapping.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Alternative methodologies to waterfall are described and compared below.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Some process models are abstract descriptions for evaluating, comparing, and improving the specific process adopted by an organization.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 12207 is the international standard describing the method to select, implement, and monitor the life cycle for software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] The Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI) is one of the leading models and is based on best practices.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Independent assessments grade organizations on how well they follow their defined processes, not on the quality of those processes or the software produced.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] ISO 9000 describes standards for a formally organized process to manufacture a product and the methods of managing and monitoring progress.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Although the standard was originally created for the manufacturing sector, ISO 9000 standards have been applied to software development as well.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Like CMMI, certification with ISO 9000 does not guarantee the quality of the end result, only that formalized business processes have been followed.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 15504 *Information technology—Process assessment*, a.k.a.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Software Process Improvement Capability Determination (SPICE), is a framework for the assessment of software processes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] This standard is aimed at setting out a clear model for process comparison.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] It models processes to manage, control, guide, and monitor software development.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] This model is then used to measure what a development organization or project team actually does during software development.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] This information is analyzed to identify weaknesses and drive improvement.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] It also identifies strengths that can be continued or integrated into common practice for that organization or team.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 24744 *Software Engineering—Metamodel for Development Methodologies*, is a power type-based metamodel for software development methodologies.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Soft systems methodology is a general method for improving management processes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-development-process] Method engineering is a general method for improving information system processes.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] System Safety is the overarching discipline that aims to achieve safety by reducing risks in technical systems to an acceptable level.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] According to the widely adopted system safety standard IEC 61508, safety is “freedom from unacceptable risk of harm”.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] As software alone – which can be considered as pure information – cannot cause any harm by itself, the term software safety is sometimes dismissed and replaced by “software system safety” (e.g. the Joint Software Systems Safety Engineering Handbook and MIL-STD-882E use this terminology).
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] This stresses that software can only cause harm in the context of a technical system (see NASA Software Safety Guidebook, chapter 2.1.2), that has some effect on its environment.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] The goal of software safety is to make sure that software does not cause or contribute to any hazards in the system where it is used and that it can be assured and demonstrated that this is the case.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] This is typically achieved by the assignment of a "safety level" to the software and the selection of appropriate processes for the development and assurance of the software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] One of the first steps when creating safety-related software is to classify software according to its safety-criticality.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Various standards suggest different levels, e.g.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Software Levels A-E in DO-178C, SIL (Safety Integrity Level) 1-4 in IEC 61508, ASIL (Automotive Safety Integrity Level) A-D in ISO 26262.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] The assignment is typically done in the context of an overarching system, where the worst case consequences of software failures are investigated.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] For example, automotive standard ISO 26262 requires the performance of a Hazard and Risk Assessment ("HARA") on vehicle level to derive the ASIL of the software executed on a component.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] It is essential to use an adequate development and assurance process, with appropriate methods and techniques, commensurate with the safety criticality of the software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Software safety standards recommend and sometimes forbid the use of such methods and techniques, depending on the safety level.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Most standards suggest a lifecycle model (e.g.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] EN 50716, SIL (Safety Integrity Level) 1-4 in IEC 61508 suggests – among others – a V-model) and prescribe required activities to be executed during the various phases of the software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] The focus on the software development and assurance process stems from the fact that software quality (and hence safety) is heavily influenced by the software process, as suggested by IEC 25010.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] It is claimed that the process influences the internal software quality attributes (e.g. code quality) and these in turn influence external software quality attributes (e.g. functionality and reliability).
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] The following activities and topics addressed in the development process contribute to safe software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Comprehensive documentation of the complete development and assurance process is required by virtually all software safety standards.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Typically, this documentation is reviewed and endorsed by third parties and therefore a prerequisite for the approval of safety-related software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] The documentation ranges from various planning documents, requirements specifications, software architecture and design documentation, test cases on various abstraction levels, tool qualification reports, review evidence, verification and validation results etc.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Fig C.2 in EN 50716 lists 32 documents that need to be created along the development lifecycle.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Traceability is the practice to establish relationships between different types of requirements and between requirements and design, implementation and testing artefacts.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] According to EN 50716, the objective “is to ensure that all requirements can be shown to have been properly met and that no untraceable material has been introduced”.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Safety standards can have requirements directly affecting the implementation of the software in source code, such as e.g. the selection of an appropriate programming language, the size and complexity of functions, the use of certain programming constructs and the need for coding standards.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Appropriate test coverage needs to be demonstrated, i.e. depending on the safety level more rigorous testing schemes have to be applied.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Software safety standards typically require some activities to be executed with independence, i.e. by a different person, by a person with different reporting lines, or even by an independent organization.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] This ensures that conflicts of interest are avoided and increases the chances that faults (e.g. in the software design) are identified.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] For example, EN 50716 Figure 2 requires the roles “implementer”, “tester” and “verifier” to be held by different people, the role “validator” to be held by a person with different reporting line and the role “assessor” to be held by a person from a different organizational unit.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] DO-178C and DO-278A require several activities (e.g. test coverage verification, assurance activities) to be executed “with independence”, with independence being defined as “separation of responsibilities which ensures the accomplishment of objective evaluation”.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] In system safety engineering, it is common to allocate upper bounds for failure rates of subsystems or components.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] It must then be shown that these subsystems or components do not exceed their allocated failure rates, or otherwise redundancy or other fault tolerance mechanisms must be employed.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] This approach is not practicable for software.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Software failure rates cannot be predicted with any confidence.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Although significant research in the field of software reliability has been conducted (see for example Lyu (1996), current software safety standards do not require any of these methods to be used or even discourage their usage, e.g.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] 73) states: “Many methods for predicting software reliability based on developmental metrics have been published, for example, software structure, defect detection rate, etc.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] This document does not provide guidance for those types of methods, because at the time of writing, currently available methods did not provide results in which confidence can be placed.” ARP 4761 clause 4.1.2 states that software design errors “are not the same as hardware failures.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Software safety and security may have differing interests in some cases.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] On the one hand safety-related software that is not secure can pose a safety risk, on the other hand, some security practices (e.g. frequent and timely patching) contradict established safety practices (rigorous testing and verification before anything is changed in an operational system).
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Software that employs artificial intelligence techniques such as machine learning follows a radically different lifecycle.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] In addition, the behavior is harder to predict than for a traditionally developed system.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Hence, the question whether and how these technologies can be used, is under current investigation.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Currently, standards generally do not endorse their use.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] For example, EN 50716 (Table A.3) states that artificial intelligence and machine learning are not recommended for any safety integrity level.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Agile software development, which typically features many iterations, is sometimes still stigmatized as being too chaotic for safety-related software development.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] This might be partially caused by statements such as "working software over comprehensive documentation", which is found in the manifesto for agile development.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] Although most software safety standards present the software lifecycle in the traditional waterfall-like sequence, some do contain statements that allow for more flexible lifecycles.
[src:iec-62304-medical/software-safety] DO-178C states that "The processes of a software life cycle may be iterative, that is, entered and reentered." EN 50716 contains Annex C that shows how iterative development lifecycles can be used in line with the requirements of the standard.
